**Clinical Reasoning:**
The central and peripheral chemoreceptors are highly sensitive to changes in arterial carbon dioxide (CO₂) levels. Increased CO₂ leads to rising hydrogen ion concentration, lowering blood pH, which directly activates the respiratory center in the medulla oblongata to stimulate deeper and faster breathing. In contrast, oxygen levels have minimal direct influence on respiratory drive—hypoxia primarily affects respiration in cases of impaired oxygenation rather than being the primary stimulus. Multiple sources emphasize that hypercapnia triggers robust, immediate responses to restore acid-base balance.

